 were both soldered and sundered by their wartime experiences. The people in this book are living sheymes - fragments of a holy book that are not to be discarded when old, but buried in consecrated ground. While embodying the world they have lost and the remnants that they carried with them, Wajnberg follows her family through their last decades. As her parents age and the author becomes their active and anxious caregiver, the book changes its perspective to accent the present - now the scene of trauma - when her parents join another demeaned group. Knowing their history, she senses that society turns away from the elderly the same way it looks away from the details of the Holocaust. Rich with humour and Yiddish idioms, Sheymes is a compelling and beautifully written memoir. In its illumination of the legacy of the Holocaust and the universal aspect of Jewish suffering, it resonates far beyond her family.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren of Holocaust survivorsxBiographyxQuébec (Province)xMontréal. 0aChildren of Holocaust survivorszQuébec (Province)zMontréalvBiography. 0aChildren of Holocaust survivorszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aDaughtersxBiographyxQuébec (Province)xMontréal. 0aDaughterszQuébec (Province)zMontréalvBiography. 0aDaughterszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aHolocaust survivorsxBiographyxQuébec (Province)xMontréal. 0aHolocaust survivorszQuébec (Province)zMontréalvBiography. 0aHolocaust survivorszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aImmigrantsxBiographyxQuébec (Province)xMontréal. 0aImmigrantszQuébec (Province)zMontréalvBiography. 0aImmigrantszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aJewish familiesxBiographyxPoland. 0aJewish familiesxBiographyxQuébec (Province)xMontréal. 0aJewish familieszPolandvBiography. 0aJewish familieszQuébec (Provinc